Novella | Frances sat on the subway & seethed. by Lara Katz Freshly smarting from her ex-boyfriend’s shocking betrayal, Frances seems bound to spiral—until the morning she runs into a nameless stranger on the subway, launching a romantic day-long exploration of Manhattan. They discuss everything from their childhoods to their futures as Frances desperately attempts to decipher this fleeting entanglement and parse out her companion, whose carefree manner belies a certain sorrow. Night is soon falling, and she—more than anyone—knows that some things are just too good to be true. In this compact and witty novella, Lara Katz winds through a heady exploration of womanhood and identity through whip-smart dialogue and sobering revelations. The unknown is not a dangerous force in this story; instead, it rejuvenates, provokes, and summons necessary challenge.Short Story Collection | Two Children by Katherine Ren“As we travel from a conversation of young souls after death to questions about our own soul future after moments of crises, Katherine Ren's short stories take us on an unpredictable journey, challenging genre and tone, always reversing our expectations. Hers is a daring and unapologetic voice that demands our attention.”  —Christina Lazaridi, Academy Award-nominated screenwriter & Creative Writing professor at Princeton University A soul-collector reckons with fading friends. The creatures of a fantastical nation are abandoned and rewritten by their disillusioned Creator. A woman who considers reconciling with her estranged mother is held up in a train station by a mysterious teenager. A girl tries to stay in her out-of-time, sepia-colored town against her brother’s wishes. A letter addressed to the reader ponders what’s been left behind. And two girls engage in bitter competition over a prize.   Through each tale in this poignant short story collection, Katherine Ren unveils layers of whimsicality and surrealism to contemplate growth and the loss of innocence. She asks what is corporeal and what is not; what truly matters and not; all underpinned by a consistent backdrop of imaginative duality. Two Children is unafraid to strike out against the reader, to force us to look back, and inwards—to resolve.<|endoftext|>What is the hosting organization of the event?<|endoftext|>

The Class of 2023 Last Lectures Commencement Committee presents its first event, The Myths that Built a Nation: Deconstructing what we know about America on Wednesday, April 19th at 4.30pm in Robertson 100 (Arthur Lewis Auditorium). Join us in conversation with Prof. Julian Zelizer, moderated by Prof. Deborah Amos, to investigate how the past is distorted in modern America, and the future challenges of American politics. The event will also focus on how graduating seniors can navigate an America rife with misinformation and misrepresentations of the past. Julian Zelizer is the Malcolm Stevenson Forbes, Class of 1941 Professor of History and Public Affairs at Princeton School of Public & International Affairs. Prof. Zelizer recently published an edited volume called 'Myth America: Historians Take on the Biggest Lies and Legends About Our Past' which he co-edited with Kevin Kruse.The event will be moderated by Deborah Amos, an international correspondent for the National Public Radio and a Ferris Professor of Journalism at Princeton University. The event is open to the entire Princeton community, and is not just limited to the Class of 2023. If you have any special request or require any accommodations, please contact Kanishkh Kanodia (kkanodia@princeton.edu).<|endoftext|>Where does this event take place?<|endoftext|>
